Research question: How did burglary and sexual assault change after the outbreak of covid19 in London? 

# Context and motivation

The international covid-19 pandemic is a period for social upheaval. It is essential to research the full impact that coronavirus and the measures enforced by governments as a result of the outbreak have on individuals and populations. Our research will contribute to the search of the impact of covid19 in London. While we will be careful not to generalize our research, if our data analysis suggests a correlation between covid19 and variation of crime statistics in 2020 then our study can be a basis for further research on the matter. 
Investigating the impact of covid19 on individuals and groups is essential. It raises awareness of the issues at hand which leads to societal sensibilization. This, in turn, can help convince individuals to respect coronavirus safety measures in order to avoid further lockdowns and protect potential victims of crimes impacted by covid safety measures. Moreover, by shedding light on the effects of the pandemic on certain offences, studies allow the government and organizations to provide support and relief for those suffering the most. For example, research on how lockdown has led to increased domestic abuse has allowed charities to provide support to victims of domestic abuse and media to raise awareness about hotlines. However, not all kinds of crimes saw an increase during the pandemic (Ashby, 2020). Regarding burglary, previous research presents conflicting results. Therefore, it is important to conduct further studies to clarify this discrepancy and to allow the government or the police to take actions. 


# Choice of variables

We chose to focus in London because as students studying here in the middle of the pandemic we wanted to investigate the impact the virus was having on our city. But most of all, many of the news articles we encountered when researching our topic were not concentrated in a certain area. Thus, we decided to conduct an in-depth city study on London. Also it is difficult to find recent and reliable data for crime rates and we were able to for London.
The time-frame we are using is 2015-2020. 

- Sexual offences


The choice of sexual offences as a variable comes from the important amount of news coverage and social media awareness campaign. However, instead of looking at only domestic abuse we thought it more interesting to look at sexual offences as a whole . We thought it necessary to add to the literature on coivd19’s impact on domestic abuse by further investigating sexual offences.         
Furthermore, our choice of variable also has a feminist motivation. Throughout history, major societal events have affected women’s rights and place in society. The coronavirus pandemic is an event of global social and one day historical significance. We wanted to therefore use our analysis of crime rates in relation to the pandemic to explore the effect it has had on women. As sexual offences are categorized as VAWG crimes, crimes primarily but not exclusively perpetrated by men against women, we thought it relevant to look at the evolution of sexual offences since the outbreak of covid19.

What do sexual offences encompass? 
There are a range of crimes that can be considered as sexual offences, including non-consensual crimes such as rape or sexual assault, crimes against children including child sexual abuse or grooming, and crimes that exploit others for a sexual purpose, whether in person or online.
This CPS approach to VAWG crimes follows United Nations conventions which the UK government has ratified, and which inform the cross-government VAWG framework. 
https://www.cps.gov.uk/crime-info/sexual-offences
The different offences that qualify as sexual offences under the law of England and Wales can be found in part one of the 2003 Sexual Assault Act. 
s.1-4: the different types of sexual offences (rape, assault by penetration, assault, causing someone to engage in sexual activity without consent).
s. 4-51 relate to offences in which children and persons with mental disorders are involved
s.51-71 relate to offences such as prostitution, trafficking and other offences
https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2003/42/contents
Under what offences is domestic abuse? 
‘Domestic abuse’ covers a range of types of abuse, including, but not limited to, psychological, physical, sexual, financial or emotional abuse. ‘Domestic abuse’ can be prosecuted under a range of offences and the term is used to describe a range of controlling and coercive behaviours, used by one person to maintain control over another with whom they have, or have had, an intimate or family relationship.
https://www.cps.gov.uk/crime-info/domestic-abuse
offences relating to domestic abuse can be found under the domestic violence, crime and victims act of 2004.
https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2004/28/contents



- Burglary
Previous studies agree about the fact that burglaries, in the absence of special circumstances such as a global pandemic, are more likely to happen in unoccupied homes (Mustaine, 1997; Tseloni et al., 2002). 

The study conducted by Ashby (2020) analyzed how different types of crime changed after the pandemic by using data from 16 different cities in the USA. When looking at burglary, the study found that in Chicago, Los Angeles, and Memphis the frequency of burglary was around half compared to what it was expected to be if covid19 never occurred. However, cities such as Austin, Louisville and Minneapolis did not experience a decrease. Moreover, out of the 11 cities that saw a decrease in burglary, in only one was the difference statistically significant. 

Another research found ambiguous results when looking at how burglaries changed after covid19 in Los Angeles (Campedelli, Aziani and Favarin, 2020). More precisely, when the authors used a univariate statistical model, the results showed an increase of 0.89% with respect to the predicted value in the absence of state’s interventions, while when they used a multivariate model, a decrease of 0.58%  was found.
Hodgkinson and Andresen (2020) looked at the effect of covid19 on residential and commercial burglary in Vancouver. This is because the likelihood of burglary is strongly related to the presence of a guardian which, during the period of lockdown, varies significantly between residential homes and stores. In fact, their research found an increase in commercial burglaries, since owners and employees were not able anymore to act as capable guardians, while residential burglary showed no obvious change. 

The inconsistency of this trend suggests that more research should be conducted around this topic. The dataset we found differentiate between residential and commercial burglaries. We will keep this distinction as we hypothesize that covid19 has a different impact on them.


- Drug offences
A recent report from the UN suggested that drug markets were likely to be affected by the COVID-19 pandemic. 
On the one hand, the report predicted an increase in drug use. Indeed, drug use has been rising for 20 years due to the population growth. However, the pandemic made the economy suffer and therefore increased unemployment while new opportunities stayed rare (UNODC, June 2020). Studies show that disadvantaged people earning less have a higher risk to face a drug use disorder which may lead them to take part in drug trafficking activities (Shaw et al., 2007). With this reasoning we would predict the number of drug offences to rise even more than what expected from March 2020.

On the other hand, the measures implemented in response to the COVID-19 spread induced a shortage of supply of certain drugs. Indeed, drug routes by air or by sea were disrupted due to closed borders and mobility restrictions (Bergeron et al., September 2020). Therefore, some criminal groups shifted their illicit drug trafficking activity towards other emerging crime opportunities like cybercrime. Others adapted their markets to the restrictions by for example, using land routes which according to the UN report has a higher control rate. As a result, more seizures are being reported on our data sources (UNODC, June 2020). This means it may not be the drug offences number that increased but the drug enforcement activities. The later point may be a limitation of our study that we have to acknowledge as it seems difficult to control it.
 
The said-complex impact of the COVID-19 on the drug offences number makes it a major variable in our crime data which in turn justify our need to use it to analyse the pandemic impact on crime in our research.

# Hypothesis
After having done an extensive literature review, we were able to formulate the following hypothesis:
Hypothesis 1: we hypothesize that the number of residential burglaries decreased after the outbreak of covid19
Hypothesis 2:  we hypothesize that the number of commercial burglaries increased after the outbreak of covid19
Hypothesis 3: we hypothesize that the number of sexual assaults changed after the outbreak of covid19
Hypothesis 4: we hypothesize that the number of drug offenses changed after the outbreak of covid19


