https://www.theguardian.com/law/2020/oct/22/prosecutions-for-crimes-against-female-victims-in-uk-dropped-amid-referral-rise-lockdown-covid Police referred more cases of violence against women and girls to the CPS across all crime types during the first three months of the pandemic, rising 5% to 64,007 from 61,179 in the previous quarter.
The number of rape cases referred increased by 15%, domestic abuse cases increased by 8% and child abuse cases rose by 9%. 
However, in the most recent quarter the volume of suspects charged (but not yet prosecuted) by the CPS across all crimes of violence against women and girls decreased by 4% from 37,403 to 35,799.CPS secretly dropped 'weak' rape cases, say rights group. 
The volume of rape cases charged by the CPS decreased from 503 in the last quarter to 487 in this quarter, a fall of 3.2%.

https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/apr/12/domestic-violence-surges-seven-hundred-per-cent-uk-coronavirus 
UK’s largest domestic abuse charity, Refuge, has reported a 700% increase in calls to its helpline in a single day, while a separate helpline for perpetrators of domestic abuse seeking help to change their behaviour received 25% more calls after the start of the Covid-19 lockdown.


# Sketch methods for presenting data
We will plot our data for each different type of crime rates on a distribution to check for skewness. 
We will plot the mode, median, mean as well
Since we are lucky enough to have data for each crime rate type per each London’s borough, we want to create a choropleth map showing how each type of crime changed in different areas of London. Instead of making one map for each crime, we are planning to create only one with a scrolling menu to choose which crime you want to visualize. 
For each crime, we will make a graph with time (from 2015 to 2019) on the x-axis and the number of crimes on the y-axis to see the trend over time and to check for points that do not follow the general trend (given by the predictive model). This will also allow us to see if there is a seasonal effect
For each crime type, we will create a graph with time (from January to October 2020) on the x-axis and number of crimes occurred on the y axis. There will be a trend line showing the predicted values of crime if COVID-19 did not occur, as well as the actual values of crime happening in 2020


# Sketch methods for analyzing data
Understanding relationships between COVID-19 and crime requires some estimate of how much crime would be expected to occur in the absence of the pandemic. Therefore, we plan to use crime data from 2015 to 2019 and use it to make a predictive model how crime rates are expected to be. We will then compare the results of the prediction with the actual crime data of 2020. The decision of using a forecast model was made based on previous literature review (Ashby, 2020; Campedelli, Aziani & Favarin, 2020; Hodgkinson & Andresen, 2020; University of Leeds, 2020).
While we could make a week-to-week or year-on-year comparisons of weekly or monthly crime counts, we thought that these comparisons risk drawing false conclusions and may not be accurate because they ignore long-term trends (which affect year-on-year comparisons) and seasonal variations (which complicate week to week comparisons) (Ashby, 2020).
A plausible forecast model is the ARIMA (autoregressive integrated moving average) model, which was used by Ashby (2020) or an interrupted time series model, which has been implemented in many researches in the criminology field (Hodgkinson & Andresen, 2020). 
We will then conduct statistical tests to check whether the difference between the predictive values and the actual values of crimes is statistically significant. This will allow us to either accept or reject our hypothesis. 


# Outline what a successful project will tell you about your domain of interest
Our results could be useful for the municipality and police forces of London, policy makers, and residents. 
If these 2 hypotehses are proven to be true, perhaps while the pandemic continues evolving, more resources can be diverted from preventing burglaries to sexual assault instead. 
More effort can also be spent on raising awareness of sexual assualt within the local London community.
This allows one to be aware of this issue and thereby be able to look out for potential signs of sexual assault that others may display. 

